  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is classified as a legally prohibited activity in virtually every country with a developed financial system. It is a serious crime with severe penalties, including imprisonment and financial sanctions.\n\nHere's why:\n\n*   **Definition:** Money laundering is the process of concealing the origins of illegally obtained money, so it appears to come from a legitimate source.\n*   **Illegality:** The act of disguising illicit funds to make them appear legal is illegal in itself. It doesn't matter if the original crime that generated the money happened in another jurisdiction.\n*   **International Laws and Regulations:** International bodies like the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) set standards for combating money laundering, and countries are expected to implement these standards in their laws.\n*   **National Laws:** Countries have their own laws that specifically prohibit money laundering. These laws typically outline the various stages of money laundering (placement, layering, integration) and prescribe penalties.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is unequivocally a legally prohibited activity.\n",
